üîπ Key Concepts of JUnit
Test Case:A single unit of testing that checks a specific functionality.
Test Suite:A collection of test cases that run together.
Assertions:Used to compare expected and actual outcomes.
Annotations:Special markers used to define methods and configurations.

# what is output
interface A {
    default void print() {
        System.out.println("Print method from A");
    }
}

interface B {
    default void print() {
        System.out.println("Print method from B");
    }
}

public class Main implements A, B {
    // Resolving conflict by overriding the print method
    @Override
    public void print() {
        // We must specify which interface method to call
        A.super.print();  // or B.super.print();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Main obj = new Main();
        obj.print(); // Output: Print method from A
    }
}
Explanation:
Diamond Problem in Interfaces:
Both A and B have a default method print(), so when Main implements both, there's a conflict.
Java does not automatically resolve this conflict, so the class must override print().
Using A.super.print();
In the overridden method, we explicitly call A.super.print();, which executes print() from A.
If we used B.super.print();, it would call print() from B.

Output:Print method from A

# What is a Setter in Java?
A setter is a method in a Java class that allows modification of private fields from outside the class. 
2. Why Use a Setter?
‚úî Encapsulation ‚Üí Keeps fields private but allows controlled modification.
‚úî Validation ‚Üí You can add checks before setting values.
‚úî Data Hiding ‚Üí Prevents direct field modification from outside.

5. When to Use and Avoid Setters
‚úî Use setters when the object needs modification after creation.
‚úî Avoid setters when designing immutable or thread-safe objects

# Cloneable Interface in Java
The Cloneable interface in Java allows objects to be copied using the clone() method. It is part of java.lang and is used to create a field-by-field copy of an object.

1. Key Points About Cloneable Interface
‚úî Marker Interface ‚Üí It does not have any methods, only acts as a flag.
‚úî Used with clone() Method ‚Üí Defined in Object class.
‚úî Throws CloneNotSupportedException if a class does not implement Cloneable.
‚úî Shallow Copy by Default ‚Üí References are copied, not deep cloned.

4. When to Use Cloneable?
‚úî When we need object duplication (e.g., creating multiple configurations).
‚úî When we need fast copying, as clone() is faster than manually copying fields.
‚úî When working with prototypes in design patterns.

5. Disadvantages of Cloneable
‚ùå Does not support deep copy by default (requires manual implementation).
‚ùå Breaks Encapsulation ‚Üí Calls super.clone(), which can copy private fields.
‚ùå Not Recommended in Modern Java ‚Üí Prefer copy constructors or serialization.

3. Important Points About clone()
It performs shallow copy (object references are copied, not new objects).
To achieve deep copy, we must override clone() in referenced objects.

class Employee implements Cloneable {
    int id;
    String name;

    public Employee(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
        return super.clone();  // Uses clone() method from Object class
    }
}
to make deep copy:
class Address implements Cloneable {
    String city;

    Address(String city) {
        this.city = city;
    }

    @Override
    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
        return new Address(this.city);  // Creating a new object (Deep copy)
    }
}

# What is the Parameter of filter() in Java Streams?
The filter() method in Java accepts a parameter of type Predicate<T>, which is a functional interface that takes an input and returns a boolean value.

Syntax of filter()
stream.filter(Predicate<T> predicate)
‚úÖ filter() retains only the elements that satisfy the condition in Predicate<T>.
exmaple:
List<Integer> evenNumbers = numbers.stream()
                .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0) // Predicate<T> checks if the number is even
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

# What is HashSet in Java?
A HashSet is a collection in Java that stores unique elements only. It is implemented using a HashMap internally, meaning elements are stored in an unordered way and have an average time complexity of O(1) for insert, remove, and search operations.
Operation	Average Case	Worst Case
Adding (add(E e))	O(1)	O(N) (In case of hash collisions)


# 1. What is Dependency Injection in Spring Boot?
Dependency Injection (DI) is a design pattern used in Spring Boot to manage object dependencies automatically instead of manually creating objects.

‚úÖ Reduces tight coupling
‚úÖ Improves maintainability
‚úÖ Makes unit testing easier

üìå How Does DI Work in Spring Boot?
Spring Boot manages dependencies using the Spring Container. The container creates and injects beans where needed.

üõ† 2. Types of Dependency Injection in Spring Boot
Spring Boot supports three types of dependency injection:

Type	                     How It's Done?	    Example
Constructor Injection	    Injects dependencies via constructor.	@Autowired on constructor
Setter Injection	        Injects dependencies via setter method.	@Autowired on setter
Field Injection	            Injects dependencies directly into fields.	@Autowired on field

# üìå @SpringBootApplication in Spring Boot
@SpringBootApplication is a meta-annotation in Spring Boot that combines three important annotations:
1Ô∏è‚É£ @Configuration ‚Üí Marks the class as a source of bean definitions.
2Ô∏è‚É£ @EnableAutoConfiguration ‚Üí Enables automatic configuration based on dependencies.
3Ô∏è‚É£ @ComponentScan ‚Üí Scans and registers components in the package and sub-packages.

üîπ Features of @SpringBootApplication
‚úî Auto Configuration ‚Üí Automatically configures Spring beans based on dependencies.
‚úî Component Scanning ‚Üí Detects components like @Service, @Repository, @Controller.
‚úî Configuration ‚Üí Acts as a Spring @Configuration class.

# que @componet @ service in my class it's is not available soes spring create bin for it
ans:
üìå @Component vs. @Service in Spring Boot
Both @Component and @Service are used for bean registration in Spring Boot, but Spring will only create a bean if the class is inside a package scanned by Spring Boot.

# que I have a class inside jar file but not anotation so how can I create bin for that class
ans:
üìå How to Create a Bean for a Class Inside a JAR Without Annotations in Spring Boot?
If a class inside a JAR file does not have annotations like @Component, @Service, or @Repository, Spring will NOT automatically create a bean for it.
However, you can manually register the class as a Spring Bean in the following ways:

üîπ 1. Using @Bean in a Configuration Class (Recommended)
You can create a bean manually in a @Configuration class using the @Bean annotation:

# üìå @Profile and @Qualifier in Spring Boot
Both @Profile and @Qualifier are used in Spring, but they serve different purposes:
@Profile ‚Üí Used for environment-specific beans.
@Qualifier ‚Üí Used for resolving multiple bean conflicts.

# üìå Handling Multiple Bean Conflicts in Spring Boot
When there are multiple beans of the same type, Spring does not know which one to inject.
Spring will throw an NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException, unless we resolve the conflict explicitly using:

1Ô∏è‚É£ @Primary ‚Üí Set a default bean.
2Ô∏è‚É£ @Qualifier ‚Üí Specify which bean to inject.
3Ô∏è‚É£ @Bean with Custom Names ‚Üí Define a bean explicitly in the @Configuration class.
4Ô∏è‚É£ @Profile ‚Üí Load beans based on environment.

# üìå Global Exception Handling in Spring Boot
In Spring Boot, we can handle exceptions globally using @ControllerAdvice and @ExceptionHandler.
This ensures that all exceptions are handled in one place instead of writing try-catch in every controller.

üîπ 1. Using @ControllerAdvice (Global Exception Handler)
We define a class with @ControllerAdvice and handle exceptions using @ExceptionHandler.

üöÄ Summary: Best Practices for Global Exception Handling

Approach	Use Case	Example Annotation
@ControllerAdvice ‚úÖ	For handling exceptions globally in controllers	@ExceptionHandler
@RestControllerAdvice ‚úÖ	For handling REST API exceptions and returning JSON responses	@RestControllerAdvice
@ResponseStatus ‚úÖ	For defining custom exceptions with HTTP status	@ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND)

# Http status code
üìå HTTP Status Codes in Java & Spring Boot
HTTP status codes indicate the result of a request made to a server. They are divided into 5 categories:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Informational (1xx)
100 Continue ‚Üí The server received the request and expects more data.
101 Switching Protocols ‚Üí The client requests switching protocols (e.g., HTTP to WebSocket).

2Ô∏è‚É£ Success (2xx)
200 OK ‚Üí Request was successful (used for GET, POST, etc.).
201 Created ‚Üí A new resource was successfully created.
204 No Content ‚Üí Request succeeded, but no response body.

‚úÖ Example in Spring Boot:
@GetMapping("/success")
public ResponseEntity<String> success() {
    return new ResponseEntity<>("Request Successful!", HttpStatus.OK);
}
3Ô∏è‚É£ Redirection (3xx)
301 Moved Permanently ‚Üí The resource has been permanently moved.
302 Found ‚Üí Temporary redirection.
304 Not Modified ‚Üí The requested resource has not changed.

‚úÖ Example of Redirecting in Spring Boot:
@GetMapping("/redirect")
public String redirect() {
    return "redirect:/new-url";  // üîπ Redirects to a new URL
}

4Ô∏è‚É£ Client Errors (4xx)
400 Bad Request ‚Üí The request is incorrect or malformed.
401 Unauthorized ‚Üí Authentication is required.
403 Forbidden ‚Üí Access is denied even if authenticated.
404 Not Found ‚Üí The requested resource is missing.
405 Method Not Allowed ‚Üí The HTTP method is not allowed for this resource.

‚úÖ Example in Spring Boot:

@GetMapping("/not-found")
public ResponseEntity<String> notFound() {
    return new ResponseEntity<>("Resource Not Found", HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND);
}

5Ô∏è‚É£ Server Errors (5xx)
500 Internal Server Error ‚Üí The server encountered an unexpected error.
502 Bad Gateway ‚Üí The server received an invalid response from an upstream server.
503 Service Unavailable ‚Üí The server is temporarily unavailable (e.g., maintenance).
504 Gateway Timeout ‚Üí The server took too long to respond.

‚úÖ Handling 500 Internal Server Error in Spring Boot:

@GetMapping("/error")
public ResponseEntity<String> internalServerError() {
    return new ResponseEntity<>("Something went wrong!", HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR);
}

# üìå Microservices Design Patterns
Microservices architecture consists of multiple independently deployable services that communicate with each other. To design scalable, resilient, and maintainable microservices, we use various design patterns.

1Ô∏è‚É£ API Gateway Pattern
‚úÖ Problem: Direct client-to-microservices communication can lead to multiple network calls and tight coupling.
‚úÖ Solution: Use an API Gateway as a single entry point to route, aggregate, and manage requests.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Circuit Breaker Pattern
‚úÖ Problem: When a microservice fails, repeated calls to it can overwhelm the system.
‚úÖ Solution: Use a circuit breaker to detect failures and stop requests temporarily.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Service Discovery Pattern
‚úÖ Problem: Microservices need a way to dynamically find and communicate with each other.
‚úÖ Solution: Use Service Discovery to register and discover services dynamically.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Saga Pattern (Distributed Transactions)
‚úÖ Problem: In microservices, a transaction spans multiple services (e.g., Order ‚Üí Payment ‚Üí Inventory).
‚úÖ Solution: Use Saga Pattern to manage distributed transactions by orchestrating or choreographing

5Ô∏è‚É£ Event-Driven Architecture (Choreography Pattern)
‚úÖ Problem: Services need to communicate asynchronously.
‚úÖ Solution: Use an event-driven approach with message brokers like Kafka or RabbitMQ.

6Ô∏è‚É£ CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation)
‚úÖ Problem: A single database for read/write operations can cause performance bottlenecks.
‚úÖ Solution: Separate read and write models.

# How Kafka Works?
Apache Kafka is a distributed event streaming platform used for real-time data processing in microservices, analytics, and event-driven applications.

üõ† Kafka Components:
Kafka follows a publish-subscribe model with the following key components:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Producer (Sends Data)
Producers send messages (events) to a Kafka topic.
Events can be anything: orders, transactions, logs, etc.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Topic (Stores Data)
A topic is like a message queue where data is stored.
Topics are partitioned, meaning data is spread across multiple nodes.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Consumer (Receives Data)
Consumers subscribe to a topic and process messages.
A Consumer Group allows multiple instances to share the load.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Broker (Manages Messages)
Kafka runs on multiple brokers (servers) that store and manage data.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Zookeeper (Manages Kafka Cluster)
Maintains metadata like leader election and consumer offsets.

üöÄ Kafka Workflow (Step-by-Step)
Producer sends data ‚Üí Kafka writes it to a topic.
Data is split into partitions and stored across brokers.
Consumers pull data from topics.
Consumer offset is tracked, ensuring no duplicate processing.

# ‚ö° Kafka vs. REST API

Feature     	Kafka (Event-Driven)	REST API (Synchronous)
Reliability	High (Event persists even if the consumer is down)	Low (Fails if the service is down)
Scalability	    Very High (Handles millions of messages)	Limited (Single request per call)
Speed	            Fast (Parallel processing)	Slower (One request at a time)

üìå When to Use Kafka?
‚úÖ Use Kafka for:
Real-time streaming (e.g., logs, monitoring, stock prices).
Microservices communication without service downtime.
Event-driven systems like order processing, fraud detection.

‚ùå Don't use Kafka for:
Small applications where simple REST APIs are enough.
Database transactions (Kafka is not a database).

# NoSQL Cache
A NoSQL Cache is a high-speed, distributed, and scalable caching layer that stores frequently accessed data in NoSQL databases like Redis, MongoDB, or Cassandra to improve performance and reduce database load.

üî• Why Use NoSQL Caching?
‚úÖ Faster Data Access ‚Äì NoSQL databases provide in-memory caching, reducing read time.
‚úÖ Scalability ‚Äì Handles millions of read requests efficiently.
‚úÖ Reduces Database Load ‚Äì Prevents frequent queries to relational databases.
‚úÖ Improves Application Performance ‚Äì Speeds up web applications and APIs.

Cache	                Type	                                        Use Case
Redis	        In-memory Key-Value Store	        Fastest caching, session storage, leaderboards

üöÄ How NoSQL Caching Works?
Client Requests Data ‚Üí Check cache (Redis, MongoDB, etc.).
If data exists in cache ‚Üí Return it (fast response).
If data is missing, fetch from the database ‚Üí Store it in the cache.
Serve the cached response next time (reducing DB calls).

# Difference Between SQL and NoSQL Databases
SQL (Relational DB)         	        NoSQL (Non-Relational DB)
Stores structured data in tables	   Stores unstructured/semi-structured data in JSON, key-value, graph format
Uses SQL Structured Query Language   	Uses NoSQL queries (MongoDB Query Language, CQL, etc.)
Supports joins between tables	         Does not support joins (denormalized data)
Use Cases:	Banking, CRM, ERP, e-commerce	Real-time analytics, IoT, social media, big data

# Hibernate Level 1 and Level 2 Caching
üõ† What is Caching in Hibernate?
Caching in Hibernate improves performance by reducing database hits by storing frequently used data in memory. Hibernate supports two levels of caching:

üîπ Level 1 Cache (L1)
‚úÖ Enabled by default (built into Hibernate).
‚úÖ Stores objects per session (valid only within a session).
‚úÖ Cached objects are removed when the session is closed.
‚úÖ Useful to avoid repeated database queries in the same transaction.
üîπ Level 2 Cache (L2)
‚úÖ Manually enabled (not by default).
‚úÖ Shared across multiple sessions and persists beyond a session.
‚úÖ Useful for reducing DB hits across transactions/users.
‚úÖ Requires third-party caching providers:EhCache,Hazelcast,Infinispan,Redis

